Anambra Governor Charles Soludo has explained why he visited the detained leader of the Indigenous People of Biafra(IPOB) Nnamdi Kanu. He made this known in a post on his Twitter page on Saturday night after visiting the IPOB leader. Soludo stated that he visited Kanu as part of his determined efforts to ensure peace, security and tranquillity back in the South East region. “I visited Mazi Nnamdi Kanu on Friday, 13th May, 2022 to felicitate with him and also as part of the wider consultations with critical stakeholders in search of lasting peace and security in the South East.   TEKAN demands justice for slain Deborah Samuel     Suspected gummen kidnap mother, children in Delta     Muslims who kill Christians in Nigeria over blasphemy…   “He was in very high spirits and we had quality and frank discussion in a very convivial atmosphere. “He expressed sadness over what he described as “sacrilegious killings” of innocent persons, kidnappings and all forms of criminalities, including the brutal enforcement of the senseless “sit at home” perpetuated by sundry groups claiming to be acting for or on behalf of IPOB. “He assured that if the opportunity arises, he will be glad to personally broadcast to his followers to maintain the peace. “Together, we shall restore peace, security and prosperity in Anambra and the Southeast. It is well indeed!”